<subsection xml:id="subsec-rotation-and-congruence" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Rotation and Congruence</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_c10e0ps8">
            <p xml:id="auto_zd9v65ox">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_1fu9hqpm">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_oeyt86bo">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qnypjuor">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_fo5n1bqb">
                        2.3 Rotation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_yv25bwbz">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_6d9fkain">
                        Deduce congruence from rotation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qi45yoox" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_zjfk8xxe">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7dgsqhvs" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ojoowbg2">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_h2z4omg8" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_4s1rn5f3"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_s94x4v41">
                        <p xml:id="auto_xygstz5l">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that rotation is a rigid transformation that preserves distance and angle. Define congruent figures as having the same shape and size. State that a figure and its image under rotation are always congruent.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_d6n990zk">
                        <p xml:id="auto_b7abbsed">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Rotate a triangle <m>90°</m> clockwise about the origin and verify congruence by comparing side lengths. Demonstrate that corresponding sides and angles are equal after rotation. Apply the distance formula to calculate side lengths of original and rotated figures.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_bzdhl25d">
                        <p xml:id="auto_18uux1wh">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Use congruence from rotation to solve geometric problems. Identify rotational symmetry in real-world objects. Explain why rotation-based designs maintain structural integrity.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
